    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sorry for bumping this very old thread, but this counterexample is currently deleted in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/31749\">#31749</a> (because with the new proposed <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=LinearOrderedCommMonoidWithZero#doc\">docs#LinearOrderedCommMonoidWithZero</a> <code>mul_pos</code> is a theorem), so I read the discussion here. One comment confuses me:<br>\n<span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110038\">Kevin Buzzard</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/mul_pos/near/226790520\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It sounds right though. I've even seen this example before. The valuation on Z_p takes values in [0,1], and now if you want to quotient and get some kind of valuation on Z/p^nZ then you need to quotient the target too, and get {0} union (1/p^n,1], and this comes up in tilting and is precisely the reason I wanted to switch from linear_ordered_comm_group_with_zero as the target of a valuation to linear_ordered_comm_monoid_with_zero.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>From the context, it seems to me that you are suggesting that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo><mo>∪</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><msup><mi>p</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{0\\} \\cup (1/p^n,1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">1/</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> is a natural example of a \"linearly ordered commutative monoid with zero\" that has <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>ϵ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\epsilon ^ 2 = 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϵ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>. Am I misunderstanding you or what is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\epsilon</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϵ</span></span></span></span> here?<br>\n(cc <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"387244\">@Yaël Dillies</span> and for reference the more recent thread where this change was discussed is here: <a class=\"stream-topic\" data-stream-id=\"287929\" href=\"/#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Should.20linear.20ordered.20comm.20monoids.20with.20zero.20be.20torsion-free/with/547548892\">#mathlib4 &gt; Should linear ordered comm monoids with zero be torsion-free</a> )</p>",
        "id": 564681602,
        "sender_full_name": "Christian Merten",
        "timestamp": 1766146078
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I assume <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\epsilon</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϵ</span></span></span></span> here would be anything between <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>p</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p^{-n}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9658em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>p</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p^{-n/2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0824em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.888em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">/2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 564684176,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1766146902
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah this is supposed to be a <em>quotient</em> of the multiplicative monoid [0,1] by the equivalence relation \"make everything in [0,1/p^n] equivalent and call it 0\" (corresponding to the quotient \"make everything with norm at most 1/p^n equal to zero\" on the ring side). Note the quotient map is an example of a non-injective morphism of monoids with trivial kernel.</p>",
        "id": 564728823,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1766159922
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So then the question is: How important is this example? Because if <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/31749\">#31749</a> is merged, this can no longer be the codomain of a valuation.</p>",
        "id": 564750494,
        "sender_full_name": "Christian Merten",
        "timestamp": 1766166950
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I can't remember what I was thinking of when I said \"this comes up in tilting\". <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110064\">@Kenny Lau</span> I was probably supervising your MSc project on tilting at that time. Do you have any memories of this?</p>",
        "id": 564777574,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1766179531
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Coming back to this: We should get to a decision on <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/31749\">#31749</a> so that Yaël does not have to keep fixing merge conflicts.<br>\nAm I correct that no one seems to remember the use case of the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo><mo>∪</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><msup><mi>p</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{0\\} \\cup (1/p^n, 1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">1/</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> example?</p>",
        "id": 566726027,
        "sender_full_name": "Christian Merten",
        "timestamp": 1767789954
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Whatever reason I had for using monoids as a target would, even if I could remember it, need to be seriously re-evaluated now we have <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ValuativeRel#doc\">docs#ValuativeRel</a> which IMO is the way to do adic spaces now. Am I right in thinking that we'd still be able to put a ValuativeRel structure on the integers corresponding to this funky thing which is about to be banned as a valuation?</p>",
        "id": 566733776,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1767792483
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I doubt so: <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ValuativeRel.vle_mul_cancel#doc\">docs#ValuativeRel.vle_mul_cancel</a> seems to forbid it</p>",
        "id": 566734975,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1767792849
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess this would not be valid because the axiom <code>vle_mul_cancel</code> would not be satisfied. My instinct is that we should do one of the following: (a) forget my concerns and go ahead, or (b) someone should actively try and get in touch with Kenny and see if he remembers anything. I'll start on (b).</p>",
        "id": 566734989,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1767792854
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/30989\">#30989</a> is Teichmuller, and I promised a future PR where I would prove <code>Perfection R ≅ Perfection (R/I)</code>, and then we won't need a valuation on <code>R/I</code> anymore, right? I don't remember anything about this valuation.</p>",
        "id": 566744895,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1767795792
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have no objections to the refactor. I don't think it's reasonable to hold this up based on some conversation from 6 years ago which nobody remembers the details of. All I know for sure is that mathlib is far more mature now.</p>",
        "id": 566772607,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1767803203
    }
]